{"updated_at": {"date": {"d": "11", "m": "07", "Y": "2026"}, "time": {"H": "04", "M": "51", "S": "20"}}, "news": [{"title": "Karnataka high court upholds uniform property tax for five-star hotels", "para": "Karnataka High Court upheld a uniform property tax for all five-star hotels. The court ruled these hotels form a distinct category for taxation purposes. This decision dismissed an appeal challenging the uniform levy across Bengaluru. The bench found no violation of constitutional equality principles. Limited relief was granted regarding penalty representation timelines.", "href": "https://realty.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/hospitality/karnataka-high-court-upholds-uniform-property-tax-for-five-star-hotels-in-bengaluru/132324441?utm_source=newslisting&utm_medium=latestNews", "img": "data:image/png;base64, ", "img-src": "https://etimg.etb2bimg.com/thumb/img-size-241018/132324441.cms?width=150&height=112", "tag": "hospitality"}, {"title": "Mumbai: Relief for Tardeo residents as BMC panel clears path to regularise OC-less buildings", "para": "Residents of Willingdon View Co-operative Housing Society face relief after a BMC proposal. This new guideline could regularize buildings that previously lacked an Occupation Certificate. Eligible buildings must have approved plans and valid commencement certificates for occupancy. Residential properties up to 80 square metres carpet area will qualify for this benefit. Residents now await the General Body's approval to begin the application process.", "href": "https://realty.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/residential/bmc-committee-approves-path-to-regularize-oc-less-buildings-relief-for-tardeo-residents/132324371?utm_source=newslisting&utm_medium=latestNews", "img": "data:image/png;base64, ", "img-src": "https://etimg.etb2bimg.com/thumb/img-size-1777940/132324371.cms?width=150&height=112", "tag": "residential"}, {"title": "MHADA 79A amendment clears legislature, revives hope for redevelopment of 13,000 old Mumbai buildings", "para": "Maharashtra's legislature has amended the MHADA Act to revive Section 79A. This amendment addresses legal ambiguities that previously halted redevelopment efforts. The state expects this change to strengthen its Supreme Court case regarding building safety. Thousands of families reside in dangerous, ageing buildings across Mumbai city. This legislative step moves forward crucial urban renewal initiatives for residents.", "href": "https://realty.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/industry/mumbais-mhada-amendment-a-lifeline-for-redeveloping-13000-dangerous-buildings/132324345?utm_source=newslisting&utm_medium=latestNews", "img": "data:image/png;base64, ", "img-src": "https://etimg.etb2bimg.com/thumb/img-size-408279/132324345.cms?width=150&height=112", "tag": "industry"}]}